\f0\fs24 \cf0 Your Bayesian intuition is well-placed. Here's the case:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 The Hebrew word 
\f4\i ratsach
\f2\i0  (
\f5 \uc0\u1512 \u1464 \u1510 \u1463 \u1495 
\f2 )
\f0\b0 \
Of the several Hebrew words that could mean killing, the Old Testament uses a fairly specific vocabulary:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-500\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f4\i\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 harag
\f0\i0\b0  \'97 general killing, slaying (used for warfare, execution, animal slaughter)\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f4\i\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 m\'fbt
\f0\i0\b0  \'97 to cause death, put to death (often judicial)\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f4\i\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 nakah
\f0\i0\b0  \'97 to strike down, smite\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f4\i\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 ratsach
\f0\i0\b0  \'97 the word used in the commandment\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The telling detail is that 
\f3\i ratsach
\f0\i0  appears almost exclusively in contexts of 
\f2\b unlawful, premeditated, or personally motivated killing
\f0\b0  \'97 not warfare, not judicial execution, not accidental death. The cities of refuge passages in Numbers 35 are particularly illuminating: they use 
\f3\i ratsach
\f0\i0  to distinguish between intentional killing and accidental killing, and even there the accidental killer is called a 
\f3\i rotseach
\f0\i0  (the noun form) \'97 but the text goes to great lengths to separate this from the "murderer" who deserves death.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 The Bayesian case:
\f0\b0 \
If we assign prior probability based on the word's ~47 appearances in the Hebrew Bible, the overwhelming contextual weight falls toward 
\f2\b intentional, unlawful killing
\f0\b0  \'97 what we'd call murder. The contexts where 
\f3\i ratsach
\f0\i0  appears that could stretch toward "kill" broadly are genuinely rare and debated even among Hebrew scholars.\
