\f2\b \cf0 The theological consequence is enormous.
\f0\b0  If the commandment is "do not kill," it creates an immediate tension with God repeatedly commanding warfare and capital punishment elsewhere in the Torah \'97 making the text internally contradictory. If it is "do not murder," that tension largely dissolves, since warfare and execution carried out under divine mandate or judicial process would fall outside 
\f3\i ratsach
\f0\i0 's semantic range.\
That internal coherence argument alone is a strong 
\f2\b ontological prior
\f0\b0  pushing toward "murder" \'97 because a text that commands something and simultaneously prohibits it is either self-defeating or requires increasingly elaborate interpretive gymnastics to rescue.\
The NIV, ESV, NASB, and most modern scholarly translations have all moved to "murder" precisely for these reasons. The KJV's "kill" (1611) reflected both the English of its era and a slightly different translational philosophy, and it pulled Catholic tradition along with it for centuries.\
So yes \'97 your Bayesian instinct is well-calibrated. "Murder" is almost certainly the more accurate rendering.\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

