\f2\b \cf0 The distributional argument:
\f0\b0 \
When the Torah's authors 
\f3\i wanted
\f0\i0  to describe warfare killing, they reached for 
\f3\i harag
\f0\i0  or 
\f3\i nakah
\f0\i0  \'97 reliably, repeatedly, ~60%+ of the time. When they wanted judicial death, they used 
\f3\i m\'fbt
\f0\i0  almost by default. The fact that 
\f3\i ratsach
\f0\i0  is used in the commandment \'97 a word with an ~85% association with unlawful/personal killing \'97 when perfectly serviceable alternatives existed for "kill" broadly, is a very strong 
\f2\b authorial intent signal
\f0\b0 .\
In Bayesian terms, this is the likelihood ratio doing heavy work. The probability that a careful Hebrew author would choose 
\f3\i ratsach
\f0\i0  if they meant generic killing is quite low \'97 maybe 5\'968% \'97 given how rarely 
\f3\i ratsach
\f0\i0  appears in those contexts and how many better words were available.\

