\f0\fs24 \cf0 This is a genuinely sharp observation, and it cuts to something important about 
\f2\b how translation choices feedback into theology
\f0\b0 , rather than just reflecting it.\
What you're describing is essentially a 
\f2\b hermeneutical loop
\f0\b0 :\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-500\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Reader encounters the OT's undeniable density of violence \'97 warfare, genocide commands, capital punishment, animal sacrifice\
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The cumulative tonal weight creates a kind of 
\f2\b semantic pressure
\f0\b0  on ambiguous words\
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Translators \'97 who are also readers, also humans, also embedded in theological communities \'97 unconsciously (or consciously) resolve ambiguity in the direction that 
\f3\i fits the tone they've already absorbed
\f0\i0 \
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 "Kill" feels right because everything 
\f3\i around
\f0\i0  it feels like killing\
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The translation then 
\f2\b reinforces
\f0\b0  that tonal reading for the next generation of readers\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 It's a confirmation bias loop operating at the civilizational timescale.\
